  "prompt": "Why does a helicopter hover, but not move with constant velocity when there is no net force?",
  "response": "When a helicopter is hovering, it is essentially maintaining a position in the air, which means it is not moving with any velocity. For an object to hover, the forces acting on it must be balanced. In the case of a helicopter, the lift generated by the rotor blades is equal to the gravitational force pulling it down. As a result, the net vertical force is zero, allowing the helicopter to maintain its altitude without ascending or descending.\n\nHowever, if we consider movement in any horizontal direction, for a helicopter to move with constant velocity, it must overcome air resistance and any other forces acting opposite to its intended direction. To achieve a constant velocity, the helicopter would need to apply a continuous, specific amount of thrust in that direction to balance out these forces and maintain an overall net force of zero. In practice, this requires careful adjustment of the rotor system to provide the necessary thrust without causing unwanted acceleration or deceleration.\n\nIn essence, hovering and moving with constant velocity require different conditions: hovering necessitates that vertical forces are balanced, while moving with constant velocity requires that all forces, both vertical and horizontal, are balanced. When a helicopter is merely hovering with no horizontal velocity, it simply maintains balance against gravity without needing to address additional horizontal forces.",
